> We've got just three words: Umami. Ginger. Sauce. Yep, this sauce truly has it all—a
> sweet, mild ginger flavor, a trace of salty soy, and a hint of heat. Mixed with Thai
> chili sauce and ponzu, our ginger sauce provides the perfect sticky coating for
> chicken over rice. Smashed cukes offer a cooling side and a pop of color, and—well,
> we lied. We've got way more than three words. But did we mention the peanuts on top?!
> Alright, we're done. You'll just have to experience this one for yourself!

In a #small pot{}, combine @jasmine rice{3/4%cup}, 1 1/4 cups water (2 cups for 4
servings), and a pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to low;
cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to
serve.

> Swap in brown rice for jasmine rice; use 1 3/4 cups water (3 1⁄2 cups for 4
> servings). Cook 20-25 minutes. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.
> (Save jasmine rice for another use.)

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{drizzle} in a small pot over medium-high heat. Add
@riiced cauliflower{12%ounce} (no need to drain), a pinch of @salt{}, and @pepper{}.
Cook, stirring occasionally, until tender, ~{6-8%minutes}. Turn off heat; stir in
@butter{1%tbsp} until melted. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

> Save jasmine rice for another use.

Wash and dry produce. Peel and mince @garlic{1%clove}(peeled and minced). Trim and
halve @mini cucumbers{2} lengthwise; cut into 1⁄2-inch-thick half-moons.

Transfer cucumbers to a #medium bowl{}; cover with @salt{pinch} and toss to coat. Let
sit for ~{3-5%minutes}, then rinse and drain. Return to bowl.

Meanwhile, pat @chopped chicken breast{10%ounce} dry with paper towels; cut into
bite-size pieces if necessary. Season with a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{drizzle} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add
chicken and cook, stirring occasionally, until browned, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Reduce heat to medium and add @umami ginger sauce{4%tbsp}, @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce},
and @ponzu sauce{18%ml} (two packets for 4 servings); cook, stirring occasionally,
until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Taste and season with salt and pepper as needed.

To bowl with cucumbers, add @gochujang sauce{1/2%ounce}, garlic, half the
@sesame oil{1%tbsp} (all for 4 servings), remaining ponzu, @sugar{1%tsp} (2 tsp for
4), and @Korean chili flakes{1%tsp} to taste. Toss to coat.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}.

Divide rice and chicken between bowls in separate sections. Top with smashed
cucumbers and @peanuts{1/2%ounce}. Serve.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165º.